<button class="accordion">What is the legal limit for the maximum weight that can be lifted in the workplace?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The guidelines suggest that the maximum weight men should lift at work is 25kg. This relates to loads held close to the body at around waist height. The recommended maximum weight is reduced to 5kg for loads being held at arm's length or above shoulder height.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are examples of moving and handling?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Manual handling refers to any activity requiring the use of force by a person to lift, lower, push, pull, hold or restrain something. Putting boxes on shelves, painting, gardening, cleaning, writing and typing are some examples of manual handling tasks.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">When should hoist be cleaned?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>For a person moving hoists, the regulations state that a hoist should be examined every six months. For other lifting equipment, every 12 months is sufficient. A competent person with practical and theoretical knowledge and experience of the lifting equipment and its use should conduct a thorough examination.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is there relevant legislation for assessing moving and handling risks?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Generally, the following legislation may be relevant for assessing moving and handling risks:</p>
<li> Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974 (HSWA)</li>
<li> Manual Handling Operations Regulations 1992 (MHOR) (as amended 2002)</li>
<li> The Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999</li>
<li> Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations 1998 (PUWER)</li>
<li> Lifting Operations and Lifting Equipment Regulations 1998 (LOLER)</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the most vulnerable part of the body when moving and handling people?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The back is the most vulnerable part of the body when poor technique is used. The lower back is subjected to ten times the weight of the object lifted.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the consequences of poor moving and handling?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Consequences of poor moving and handling can be categorised into three main areas, including short term and superficial injuries, long term injuries and mental health issues.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How do you move and handle patients?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>If you've assessed the situation and have decided to move the person, make sure you:</p>
<li> Never lift above shoulder height/li>
</li><li> Keep your feet stable</li>
<li> Have a firm hold</li>
<li> Keep any weight close to your body</li>
<li> Keep your back straight and bend your knees</li>
<li> Lift as smoothly as possible.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How can employers reduce risks of injury in the health and social care settings?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Employers must reduce the risk of injury to staff and people using care services by:</p>
<li> Avoiding manual handling tasks that could result in injury, where reasonably practicable</li>
<li> Assessing the risks from moving and handling that cannot be avoided</li>
<li> Putting measures in place to reduce the risk, where reasonably possible.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why is dealing with moving and handling necessary?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Moving and handling injuries can have severe implications for the employer and the person who has been injured. They can occur almost anywhere in the workplace, and heavy manual labour, awkward postures, repetitive movements of arms, legs and back or previous/existing injury can increase the risk.</p>
</div>
